  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real, felt pressure that echoes in every interaction I've had as someone who's watched her own family navigate the academic and professional world. My father, a PhD, taught me to love learning, but his own experiences with being the 'only one' in his field left scars that still resonate. When I was in school, I remember sitting in math class, the quiet dread of knowing that my teachers would see me as 'not a math person' before they even saw my work. That's stereotype threat: the anxiety of being judged by a group label rather than your actual ability. As a woman in New York who's been depressed for years, I've seen how this fear can make people withdraw, especially in fields where they're underrepresented. Should we address it? Absolutely. But not with top-down solutions that ignore the human experience. I've volunteered at community centers, and I've seen how small, consistent acts of encouragement—like a teacher saying 'I believe in you' instead of 'you're not cut out for this'—can make a difference. The key is to create spaces where people feel safe to fail without being labeled. My depression makes me hyper-aware of how much mental health impacts our ability to engage with systems that don't support us. So yes, we must address stereotype threat in STEM, but it starts with listening, not lecturing. We need to build environments where everyone feels seen, not just the 'right' people.",
